not necessarily, most important thing is thinner ropes are lighter and often easier to clip into quick draws, but thicker ropes are somewhat stronger. Static ropes just mean that they don‚Äôt stretch as much to dissipate force, but that also means they are a bit stronger

I do get bored sometimes, but I really try to not get bored because being bored for me is a pretty bad thing. Being bored for me isn't when I'm doing something that is generally boring, but it's doing something that leads to me feeling like I'm not being productive for others or for myself. So lying on a couch all day after a super long week feels productive sometimes because I need to restore my physical or emotional wellbeing. But when I don't feel like I'm gaining any fulfillment out of doing something, that's when I get bored. And that's when I get depressed.

ok so the phones are satellite, so anywhere with a clear view of the sky you get service. They cannot call, but can send, receive and view text messages. They can send or receive messages from any cell phone. They have to be activated before you can use them, which is expensive. They have a yearly registration fee, and a monthly activation fee. We registered them right before wp, so its possible that if you call the company, you could convince them to let you activate them for may trip without registering them for another year, and save a little money. So when you activate them, you set them up connect with a person and put in phone numbers for emergency contacts. We used stan and amy for those contacts. The sat phones have an emergency button you can press, which will send medical help to your location and send an emergency message with your location to the emergency contacts. The phones also have an accompanying phone app that people should download. The phone app lets you upload things like topographic maps of the area and makes using the phone easier. You can track where the phones are from the app, or from a computer. The sat phones can record their gps coordinates and other people can view those coordinates from their phone app. I wasn‚Äôt on trail so i didn‚Äôt actually use them a ton, but I would ask some other trail leaders from last year, or julia and steph, to see how they actually used them on trail. They take a little bit to activate and set up, so you might wanna do that a day or two before hand. Any other questions?! Also how was may trip?!! you have a good time?

to Alex 
Alex,

First, I would like to remind you that the wash u climbing club is a student run organization. We are not paid to run the club; it is not our job to sit at the computer replying to emails and we do not check our email every hour. 

Actually, the club is organized by volunteers like myself, who love the sport and the community it fosters. We make an effort to include new people and add to the community of the team. Currently, there are 150 club members and 30+ team members, so you are not the only person who needs attention. 

Now before you start making "demands", I want you to pause and consider how you are approaching this situation. Is it possible we made a mistake and missed adding you to the groupMe? Is it possible that we don't check the email an hour before practice because we have other responsibilities? Or is it more likely that we "doing all we can to actively drive prospective members away". After tabling to sell memberships for over 6 hours the past few days, and sending several emails about the team, I would disagree with that statement. 

So heres the deal. I will add you to the groupMe and you are encouraged to come to practice on thursday (you aren't the only new member who is interested but missed the first practice). BUT, if you come to participate, your attitude needs to be different. The team is a community that is patient, supportive and respectful. I look forward to having you as a part of the team in a way that is inclusive and positive.

Best,
Lucas

We plan to work with Jimmy Xu to create his Interventional Radiology app idea. As discussed in his presentation, the app would serve to eliminate the mental gymnastics that doctors must perform when simultaneously working with patients and looking up at monitors. Using an iPad that can be positioned over the patients body, we can use AR to enhance the process of Radiology procedures.

This is the functionality Jimmy is looking for:

‚ÄúSo the way I was sort of envisioning it is that the image would overlie the area of anatomic interest. For example, if we are interested in placing an abscess drain in the left lower quadrant of the abdomen, we would be focusing our imaging over there. We could place an image target in that area and the app would automatically project an image over there.¬†

The operator will need some limited ability to manipulate the images. So what frequently happens is that we'll start with a reference image called a "scout" over the area. As the procedure progresses more images are taken. So the ability to cache images at another location and recall them over the area of interest¬†as necessary.

Other useful actions would be to rotate the image along its xyz axes and to magnify. If you could play video that would be helpful as well because a lot of the imaging is dynamic as we inject contrast.‚Äù
